Task 2-A04: Cryptographic Failures:

          Cryptographic failures occur when sensitive data isn’t properly protected due to missing or weak encryption,
poor implementation, or inadequate security practices.

Examples include:
          • Storing passwords without hashing 
          • Using outdated or weak algorithms (MD5, SHA-1, DES)
          • Exposing encryption keys
          • Failing to secure data in transit A classic mistake is “rolling your own cryptography”
          instead of using proven, vetted algorithms.

Prevention
          • Use strong, modern algorithms and trusted libraries for encryption
          • Hash passwords with bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2
          • Never embed secrets or credentials in code or config files
          • Use secure key management systems to store secrets
          • Ensure data in transit and at rest is properly encrypted

