Ans: THM{WEAK_CRYPTO_FLAG}

Task 3-A05: Injection:

            Injection occurs when an application mishandles user input, passing it directly into a system that can execute
commands or queries, such as a database, shell, templating engine, or API.
A classic example is SQL Injection, where user input (like a username) is directly used to build a query without
sanitization. Other types include:
                      • Command Injection
                      • SQL Injection
                      • Server-Side Template Injection (SSTI)
                      • AI Prompt Injection
                      Injection remains highly critical, as attackers can manipulate input to steal data, bypass authentication, or
                      execute commands.
Prevention
          • Treat all user input as untrusted
          • Use prepared statements or parameterized queries
          instead of string concatenation for SQL
          • Avoid passing input directly to system commands; use safe APIs instead
          • Validate and sanitize input: enforce strict data types,escape dangerous characters, and filter before
          processing .
          • Apply consistent input handling across all user entry points

Q1: Perform an SSTI attack on the practical. You need to read the contents of flag.txt that is located
within the same directory as the web application.
Ans: THM{SSTI_FLAG_OBTAINED}


Task 4-A08: Software or Data Integrity Failures:

Software or Data Integrity Failures (A08)

These failures occur when an application trusts code,
updates, or data without verifying their authenticity,
integrity, or origin. Examples include:
                • Installing software updates without verification
                • Loading scripts or configuration files from untrusted sources
                • Accepting unvalidated data (binaries, templates, JSON) that affects application logic
Attackers can exploit these weaknesses to inject malicious code, alter behaviour, or compromise sensitive data.
Prevention
            • Establish clear trust boundaries for code, updates, and data
            • Verify all updates and critical files using cryptographic checks (checksums, signatures)
            • Ensure only trusted sources can modify critical components
            • Integrate integrity verification into CI/CD pipelines and build processes
